msgid "Virtualization Technology"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: abstract/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:17
msgid "Virtualization is a technology that provides a way for a machine (Host) to run another operating system (guest virtual machines) on top of the host operating system."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/title
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:25
msgid "Overview"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:29
msgid "<phrase role=\"productname\"><phrase os=\"osuse\">openSUSE Leap</phrase><phrase os=\"sles\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Server</phrase><phrase os=\"sled\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Desktop</phrase><phrase os=\"slerte\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Real Time Extension</phrase></phrase> includes the latest open source virtualization technologies, Xen and KVM. With these Hypervisors, <phrase role=\"productname\"><phrase os=\"osuse\">openSUSE Leap</phrase><phrase os=\"sles\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Server</phrase><phrase os=\"sled\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Desktop</phrase><phrase os=\"slerte\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Real Time Extension</phrase></phrase> can be used to provision, de-provision, install, monitor and manage multiple virtual machines (VM Guests) on a single physical system (for more information see <xref linkend=\"gloss.vt.hypervisor\"/>)."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:36
msgid "Out of the box, <phrase role=\"productname\"><phrase os=\"osuse\">openSUSE Leap</phrase><phrase os=\"sles\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Server</phrase><phrase os=\"sled\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Desktop</phrase><phrase os=\"slerte\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Real Time Extension</phrase></phrase> can create virtual machines running both modified, highly tuned, paravirtualized operating systems and fully virtualized unmodified operating systems. Full virtualization allows the guest OS to run unmodified and requires the presence of AMD64/Intel 64 processors which supports either Intel* Virtualization Technology (Intel VT) or AMD* Virtualization (AMD-V))."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:45
msgid "The primary component of the operating system that enables virtualization is a Hypervisor (or virtual machine manager), which is a layer of software that runs directly on server hardware. It controls platform resources, sharing them among multiple VM Guests and their operating systems by presenting virtualized hardware interfaces to each VM Guest."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:53
msgid "<phrase os=\"sles;sled\">SUSE Linux Enterprise is an enterprise-class</phrase><phrase os=\"osuse\">openSUSE is a</phrase> Linux server operating system that offers two types of Hypervisors: Xen and KVM. Both Hypervisors support virtualization on 64-bit x86-based hardware architectures. Both Xen and KVM support full virtualization mode. In addition, Xen supports paravirtualized mode. <phrase role=\"productname\"><phrase os=\"osuse\">openSUSE Leap</phrase><phrase os=\"sles\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Server</phrase><phrase os=\"sled\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Desktop</phrase><phrase os=\"slerte\">SUSE Linux Enterprise Real Time Extension</phrase></phrase> with Xen or KVM acts as a virtualization host server (<xref linkend=\"gloss.vt.vhs\"/>) that supports VM Guests with its own guest operating systems. The SUSE VM Guest architecture consists of a Hypervisor and management components that constitute the VHS, which runs many application-hosting VM Guests."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:66
msgid "In Xen, the management components run in a privileged VM Guest often called <xref linkend=\"gloss.vt.dom0\"/>. In KVM, where the Linux kernel acts as the hypervisor, the management components run directly on the VHS."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/title
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:73
msgid "Virtualization Capabilities"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:75
msgid "Virtualization design provides many capabilities to your organization. Virtualization of operating systems is used in many computing areas:"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: listitem/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:83
msgid "Server consolidation: Many servers can be replaced by one big physical server, so hardware is consolidated, and Guest Operating Systems are converted to virtual machine. It provides the ability to run legacy software on new hardware."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: listitem/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:91
msgid "Isolation: guest operating system can be fully isolated from the Host running it. So if the virtual machine is corrupted, the Host system is not harmed."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: listitem/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:98
msgid "Migration: A process to move a running virtual machine to another physical machine. Live migration is an extended feature that allows this move without disconnection of the client or the application."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: listitem/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:105
msgid "Disaster recovery: <xref linkend=\"gloss.vt.virtualized\"/> guests are less dependent on the hardware, and the Host server provides snapshot features to be able to restore a known running system without any corruption."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: listitem/para
#: xml/vt_introduction.xml:113
msgid "Dynamic load balancing: A migration feature that brings a simple way to load-balance your service across your infrastructure."
msgstr ""

